00:06:35.710 --> 00:06:38.350
And what my research
focused on was

00:06:38.350 --> 00:06:41.912
trying to look at some of the
drivers of behavioral change.

00:06:41.912 --> 00:06:45.170
Are there are emotional
triggers that we can identify?

00:06:45.170 --> 00:06:47.830
And are there maps,
connection points?

00:06:47.830 --> 00:06:50.780
And again, my business
is I'm an agency girl.

00:06:50.780 --> 00:06:53.520
I've grown up in agencies
and communication.

00:06:53.520 --> 00:06:56.384
So I take this from a
communications perspective.

00:06:56.384 --> 00:06:57.800
I'm not a behavioral
psychologist.

00:06:57.800 --> 00:07:01.230
I'm a communications person.

00:07:01.230 --> 00:07:04.790
Our research started by asking
people to self-identify.

00:07:04.790 --> 00:07:06.610
And we looked at the
cohorts on the right--

00:07:06.610 --> 00:07:09.890
the baby boomers, the Gen
X'ers, the Millennials.

00:07:09.890 --> 00:07:14.250
And I don't use those terms,
those cohorts, very often.

00:07:14.250 --> 00:07:16.490
But sometimes, in terms
of research like this,

00:07:16.490 --> 00:07:18.530
it just makes it easier.

00:07:18.530 --> 00:07:21.750
We asked people to
self-identify by age.

00:07:21.750 --> 00:07:25.135
And you think about things
like risk taking and ambition.

00:07:25.135 --> 00:07:26.010
And that makes sense.

00:07:26.010 --> 00:07:28.510
The younger you are, the middle
part you are in your career,

00:07:28.510 --> 00:07:31.950
somewhere to 30 to 54, you're
going to be more risky.

00:07:31.950 --> 00:07:35.180
Probably is true with your
stock investments as well.

00:07:35.180 --> 00:07:37.290
It's interesting to see
how optimism changes.

00:07:37.290 --> 00:07:39.287
You tend to-- from
our research, this

00:07:39.287 --> 00:07:41.120
is six months old--
tend to be a little more

00:07:41.120 --> 00:07:44.350
optimistic before you turn 55.

00:07:44.350 --> 00:07:48.090
But the one thing that united
every age group that people

00:07:48.090 --> 00:07:52.010
self-identified with, when
chosen, was compassion.

00:07:52.010 --> 00:07:54.730
So when you're
thinking about a brand

00:07:54.730 --> 00:07:57.040
and you're thinking about
you reaching an individual,

00:07:57.040 --> 00:07:59.040
yes, you might be
reaching an engineer.

00:07:59.040 --> 00:08:00.810
You might be reaching a doctor.

00:08:00.810 --> 00:08:03.760
You might be reaching
a small business owner.

00:08:03.760 --> 00:08:06.280
But you are reaching
a human being

00:08:06.280 --> 00:08:08.850
that, in most
circumstances, truly

00:08:08.850 --> 00:08:12.450
values that compassion is
really relevant to them.

00:08:12.450 --> 00:08:16.260
So once you think about the fact
of how people self-identify,

00:08:16.260 --> 00:08:20.040
you ask people what is
relevant to them personally.

