00:25:36.600 --> 00:25:38.560
with the people that
we were giving to

00:25:38.560 --> 00:25:43.870
so that great work keeps
propagating itself?

00:25:43.870 --> 00:25:46.240
Really interesting, this
sort of explains to me

00:25:46.240 --> 00:25:48.720
the state of
affairs on politics.

00:25:48.720 --> 00:25:52.400
But people, what's really
important to people

00:25:52.400 --> 00:25:56.960
is when they vote for a
candidate is they like them.

00:25:56.960 --> 00:25:59.070
When it gets down to the
functional side, when

00:25:59.070 --> 00:26:02.951
you start talking about,
what's their track record?

00:26:02.951 --> 00:26:04.950
You really start looking
into their backgrounds,

00:26:04.950 --> 00:26:06.616
you'd think a lot of
people would really

00:26:06.616 --> 00:26:09.140
concentrate on the
functional aspects.

00:26:09.140 --> 00:26:13.110
The data is showing people
look at candidates and say,

00:26:13.110 --> 00:26:13.820
I like them.

00:26:13.820 --> 00:26:17.130
I like the way
they-- I mean, they

00:26:17.130 --> 00:26:21.260
seem to stand for
the same things I do.

00:26:21.260 --> 00:26:23.990
I associate it with values
that are important to me.

00:26:23.990 --> 00:26:28.140
It's very, very
values, ethics driven.

00:26:28.140 --> 00:26:31.410
And you can see why the
divides exist amongst parties,

00:26:31.410 --> 00:26:33.950
because there are so many
different slices of values

00:26:33.950 --> 00:26:36.260
and ethics in our nation.

00:26:36.260 --> 00:26:38.980
So if you take a look
at collapsing the three

00:26:38.980 --> 00:26:43.340
elements on this slide, you can
see that different sectors have

00:26:43.340 --> 00:26:45.810
different balances,
different quadrant balances,

00:26:45.810 --> 00:26:46.930
of relevance.

00:26:46.930 --> 00:26:48.530
But there's such an opportunity.

00:26:48.530 --> 00:26:50.800
And their balanced
for a good reason.

00:26:50.800 --> 00:26:55.600
So my argument is,
I'm not suggesting

00:26:55.600 --> 00:26:57.330
make all quadrants equal.

00:26:57.330 --> 00:26:59.930
I'm not suggesting don't
lead where your strength is.

00:26:59.930 --> 00:27:01.620
But what I'm
suggesting, there are

00:27:01.620 --> 00:27:05.750
insights that you can find from
the other three quadrants that

00:27:05.750 --> 00:27:09.600
can add a tremendous
emotional dimension

00:27:09.600 --> 00:27:14.830
to the creative product that
you're putting out there

00:27:14.830 --> 00:27:15.880
for people.

00:27:15.880 --> 00:27:17.650
And I think we're
beginning to see

00:27:17.650 --> 00:27:21.670
that the analytics and the
data do support creating

00:27:21.670 --> 00:27:24.110
an insight that is
tremendously unique

00:27:24.110 --> 00:27:27.660
and that's derived from a
very holistic look at a person

00:27:27.660 --> 00:27:30.590
rather than just a
functional look at a person.

00:27:30.590 --> 00:27:32.870
So here's some fresh new data.

00:27:32.870 --> 00:27:34.000
It's a law firm.

00:27:34.000 --> 00:27:37.090
You're thinking
about a law firm.

00:27:37.090 --> 00:27:40.540
You're in the room
with your parents.

00:27:40.540 --> 00:27:42.954
You both are thinking,
well, the firm I choose

00:27:42.954 --> 00:27:44.870
will be the one with the
most successful track

00:27:44.870 --> 00:27:46.245
record with the
greatest clients,

00:27:46.245 --> 00:27:49.440
the greatest number
of cases won.

00:27:49.440 --> 00:27:50.750
Is it a firm that I know?

00:27:50.750 --> 00:27:53.280
Is it one I can
personally trust?

00:27:53.280 --> 00:27:54.550
The firm, is it a social?

00:27:54.550 --> 00:27:56.780
So for example, does it
have a really good track

00:27:56.780 --> 00:27:58.740
record with social causes?

00:27:58.740 --> 00:28:01.760
Is it recommended by a friend
or a family member or someone

00:28:01.760 --> 00:28:04.730
in my business?

00:28:04.730 --> 00:28:09.290
Or is finding a relationship
inside a firm with someone

00:28:09.290 --> 00:28:11.030
that's really
committed to helping

00:28:11.030 --> 00:28:14.550
me have a successful
outcome, that emotion?

00:28:14.550 --> 00:28:17.490
Sort of falls more in
the sensory bucket.

00:28:17.490 --> 00:28:23.240
And it's really interesting to
say that the whole red quadrant

00:28:23.240 --> 00:28:25.530
lower right is the
firm I choose will

00:28:25.530 --> 00:28:27.530
be the one I can
personally trust.

00:28:27.530 --> 00:28:30.550
37% that was important to.

00:28:30.550 --> 00:28:36.800
27% was the firm that was--
and this is collectively--

00:28:36.800 --> 00:28:39.320
was the firm that helped
the individual achieve

00:28:39.320 --> 00:28:41.110
a successful outcome.

00:28:41.110 --> 00:28:43.560
The firm I choose will
be the one recommended

00:28:43.560 --> 00:28:47.630
by another person, and then
finally the track record.

00:28:47.630 --> 00:28:50.220
But it's interesting,
the youngest people

00:28:50.220 --> 00:28:54.470
in our survey cared about
the track record the most.

00:28:54.470 --> 00:29:01.730
And the older people, especially
in the 55 to 64-year-old range,

00:29:01.730 --> 00:29:05.030
really care about the
commitment to the outcome.

00:29:05.030 --> 00:29:08.640
So the lesson for us as
branders and marketers

00:29:08.640 --> 00:29:10.150
is relevance changes.

00:29:10.150 --> 00:29:12.850
Relevance changes.

00:29:12.850 --> 00:29:14.340
It's circumstantial.

00:29:14.340 --> 00:29:18.750
It changes with
how your life goes.

00:29:18.750 --> 00:29:21.450
And it changes with
different situations.

00:29:21.450 --> 00:29:22.990
It's very situational.

00:29:22.990 --> 00:29:26.640
But the things-- and you'll
see also in banking--

00:29:26.640 --> 00:29:30.260
that there's a trend to, in
the early parts of our lives,

00:29:30.260 --> 00:29:33.835
we're thinking about maximizing
returns all the time.

00:29:33.835 --> 00:29:35.960
Our data started to show
that people would actually

00:29:35.960 --> 00:29:40.436
forego $1 of profit for a
long-standing relationship

00:29:40.436 --> 00:29:41.810
with a financial
institution that

00:29:41.810 --> 00:29:43.920
cared about you
across your lifetime.

00:29:43.920 --> 00:29:46.830
So again, we asked them the
same sorts of questions.

00:29:46.830 --> 00:29:49.720
I just gave you a
sneak peek into this.

00:29:49.720 --> 00:29:53.240
The two leading
quadrants were one

00:29:53.240 --> 00:29:58.120
about firms I know are used
by people I trust and respect.

00:29:58.120 --> 00:30:00.000
So word of mouth,
very, very important

00:30:00.000 --> 00:30:01.610
in financial services.

00:30:01.610 --> 00:30:03.610
And the second one
was saving money.

00:30:06.120 --> 00:30:10.840
The digital ease of use
was the smallest slice,

00:30:10.840 --> 00:30:13.550
but most important, you'll
see, to the youngest audience.

00:30:13.550 --> 00:30:17.430
And then this, the red part,
became very, very important

00:30:17.430 --> 00:30:19.340
to people as they age.

00:30:19.340 --> 00:30:23.450
So you can see how the
data kind of-- this chart

00:30:23.450 --> 00:30:26.720
explains what I just said.

00:30:26.720 --> 00:30:30.150
So I don't know if any
of you in this room

00:30:30.150 --> 00:30:32.490
are still paying
off college loans.

00:30:32.490 --> 00:30:33.410
I know I'm a parent.

00:30:33.410 --> 00:30:36.180
I have three boys in college.

00:30:36.180 --> 00:30:40.090
I was really fascinated with
the results of this survey.

00:30:40.090 --> 00:30:42.700
So if you're thinking
about choosing a college--

00:30:42.700 --> 00:30:46.870
and we looked, again, same
age spectrum-- what do you

00:30:46.870 --> 00:30:47.710
care about?

00:30:47.710 --> 00:30:50.040
Do you care about a
learning experience

00:30:50.040 --> 00:30:52.610
that can help you
prepare for a career?

00:30:52.610 --> 00:30:54.720
Do you care about a
learning experience

00:30:54.720 --> 00:30:57.060
that socially connects
you to other people?

00:30:57.060 --> 00:31:00.210
Is it your network you
get when you graduate?

00:31:00.210 --> 00:31:05.590
Is it about an experience that
changes or shapes your values?

00:31:05.590 --> 00:31:07.990
Or is it about
just something that

00:31:07.990 --> 00:31:11.180
creates an overall
positive experience?

00:31:11.180 --> 00:31:15.810
Well, unequivocally,
getting a job,

00:31:15.810 --> 00:31:19.080
having an experience that
leads to a successful outcome

00:31:19.080 --> 00:31:21.820
where you are employed
is incredibly important.

00:31:21.820 --> 00:31:24.420
It's incredibly
important to people

00:31:24.420 --> 00:31:26.220
who are in college,
who have recently

00:31:26.220 --> 00:31:28.590
graduated from college,
or who are currently

00:31:28.590 --> 00:31:31.210
paying for their
kids' college, or who

00:31:31.210 --> 00:31:32.820
are paying off their loans.

00:31:32.820 --> 00:31:37.700
So again, looking
at 10 years ago,

00:31:37.700 --> 00:31:39.874
I think this would have
been very, very different.

00:31:39.874 --> 00:31:42.040
I think the social networks,
if we'd have done this,

00:31:42.040 --> 00:31:44.320
would have been very, very
important-- who you know,

00:31:44.320 --> 00:31:45.560
who you meet.

00:31:45.560 --> 00:31:49.140
Those are the tickets to
getting you a job later in life.

00:31:49.140 --> 00:31:50.790
So again, this is the breakdown.

00:31:50.790 --> 00:31:54.400
This shows how a college
university or learning

00:31:54.400 --> 00:31:56.650
experience can prepare
you for a career.

00:31:56.650 --> 00:32:01.046
Clearly, the leading indicator
across all age cohorts.

00:32:01.046 --> 00:32:02.680
Very interesting.

00:32:02.680 --> 00:32:05.100
So I've told you,
this is survey work.

00:32:05.100 --> 00:32:07.500
So this is a lot of
marketing survey work.

00:32:07.500 --> 00:32:09.180
There are also
pieces of relevance

00:32:09.180 --> 00:32:12.760
that you can get which I just
call that are circumstantially.

00:32:12.760 --> 00:32:15.090
And we look across one
of the tools we have,

00:32:15.090 --> 00:32:17.400
it's a software product
that recognizing

00:32:17.400 --> 00:32:19.050
keywords or phrases.

00:32:19.050 --> 00:32:22.540
So we can look across
the social platforms.

00:32:22.540 --> 00:32:24.630
And for example,
if we're looking

00:32:24.630 --> 00:32:27.610
for a luxury good
hotel, we can see

00:32:27.610 --> 00:32:30.410
how people, words,
or phrases that

00:32:30.410 --> 00:32:33.011
are used in conversation or
dialogue that are associated

00:32:33.011 --> 00:32:35.510
with Hilton, that are associated
with the Four Seasons, that

00:32:35.510 --> 00:32:37.670
might be associated
with the Ritz Carlton.

00:32:37.670 --> 00:32:43.050
And I use this example
because it's, we found,

00:32:43.050 --> 00:32:44.670
a very, very
interesting insight.

00:32:44.670 --> 00:32:46.900
We were looking at
luxury categories.

00:32:46.900 --> 00:32:49.160
We had done our qualitative
and quantitative research.

00:32:49.160 --> 00:32:51.290
We'd done all the
relevance profiles.

00:32:51.290 --> 00:32:54.430
We saw this comment that
just kept cropping up

00:32:54.430 --> 00:32:56.710
about Ritz Carlton hotels.

00:32:56.710 --> 00:32:59.490
And the online dialogue,
the words and phrases

00:32:59.490 --> 00:33:03.480
were all talking about the
water temperature and pressure

00:33:03.480 --> 00:33:04.830
of Ritz Carlton hotels.

00:33:04.830 --> 00:33:07.210
And they said, if you
are a business traveler,

00:33:07.210 --> 00:33:09.260
you have got to stay
at a Ritz Carlton.

00:33:09.260 --> 00:33:12.720
There's no better shower in
the world if you're traveling.

00:33:12.720 --> 00:33:15.140
It's the temperature,
it's the pressure.

00:33:15.140 --> 00:33:18.010
It's better than the coffee
or the great-smelling lobby,

00:33:18.010 --> 00:33:19.950
or the soft towels,
or whatever it is.

00:33:19.950 --> 00:33:21.630
It's the water
temperature and pressure.

00:33:21.630 --> 00:33:23.420
You would have never
thought of that

00:33:23.420 --> 00:33:26.330
when you were doing your
IDIs and interviewing people

00:33:26.330 --> 00:33:28.390
about why they
choose hotel brands.

00:33:28.390 --> 00:33:32.080
And that's an insight
that's very situational

00:33:32.080 --> 00:33:33.780
that comes up out of nowhere.

00:33:33.780 --> 00:33:37.540
And you have to allow for
that in your branding process.

00:33:37.540 --> 00:33:41.420
You have to allow for stuff that
isn't structured to come up,

00:33:41.420 --> 00:33:43.510
because some of the
greatest bits of creativity

00:33:43.510 --> 00:33:45.020
come from that.

00:33:45.020 --> 00:33:50.500
So how this all works is you
go through a methodology that

00:33:50.500 --> 00:33:53.960
tries to get at the
very unique insights,

00:33:53.960 --> 00:33:57.170
slicing and dicing it every
way, I showed you the data.

00:33:57.170 --> 00:34:00.240
Once you have a couple of
insights you want to test,

00:34:00.240 --> 00:34:04.870
you can use this M3
methodology that we've

00:34:04.870 --> 00:34:07.370
developed with our partner,
which just allows you--

00:34:07.370 --> 00:34:10.540
it's an algorithm-- and
it allows you to choose

00:34:10.540 --> 00:34:12.980
your favorite choice and
your least favorite choice.

00:34:12.980 --> 00:34:16.449
So you'd get 16
screens of a choice.

00:34:16.449 --> 00:34:18.570
This most reflects
my preference,

00:34:18.570 --> 00:34:19.909
this least reflects.

00:34:19.909 --> 00:34:25.010
And what it allows you to
do is find the precise mix

00:34:25.010 --> 00:34:28.480
of messages that support
your insight that

00:34:28.480 --> 00:34:29.989
get you the maximum reach.

00:34:29.989 --> 00:34:32.510
So for example, I would
be able to figure out,

00:34:32.510 --> 00:34:35.210
once I knew something
more about you,

00:34:35.210 --> 00:34:38.480
what four combinations
of messages

00:34:38.480 --> 00:34:40.159
I might need to
communicate to you

00:34:40.159 --> 00:34:43.440
to sell you a new bike, for
example, or a new camera.

00:34:43.440 --> 00:34:46.130
Those, you can get very,
very specific with it.

00:34:46.130 --> 00:34:48.442
And it takes some of
the risk out of it.

00:34:48.442 --> 00:34:50.900
And you can see here, this is
an example of just the sample

00:34:50.900 --> 00:34:54.489
size, how it changes when
you test the messages.

00:34:54.489 --> 00:34:57.510
The other lesson
is, people think

00:34:57.510 --> 00:35:00.540
it's really easy for people
that are driving brands,

00:35:00.540 --> 00:35:03.840
or they make products,
to assume that they think

00:35:03.840 --> 00:35:06.640
they know what the messages
are, and you learn so much

00:35:06.640 --> 00:35:09.660
about testing with
just asking people.

00:35:09.660 --> 00:35:12.430
Because sometimes the things you
assume are going to be correct

00:35:12.430 --> 00:35:13.940
aren't.

00:35:13.940 --> 00:35:16.450
So I mean, at the
end of the day,

00:35:16.450 --> 00:35:18.730
this is sort of, towards
the end of things,

00:35:18.730 --> 00:35:22.330
we've done this with a bunch of
clients over the last 25 years

00:35:22.330 --> 00:35:24.020
from financial
services companies

00:35:24.020 --> 00:35:27.740
to medical device companies
that are introducing power

00:35:27.740 --> 00:35:32.670
sutures to pharmaceutical
companies to nonprofits.

00:35:32.670 --> 00:35:35.370
And relevance, if
I could tell you

00:35:35.370 --> 00:35:38.260
seven things that are
really important--

00:35:38.260 --> 00:35:40.820
and this can be true for
building personal relevance,

00:35:40.820 --> 00:35:44.670
like in your job or your
team-- is the best brands

00:35:44.670 --> 00:35:46.380
are movements, not products.

00:35:46.380 --> 00:35:48.710
They're the things that
you spark an insight that

00:35:48.710 --> 00:35:52.400
gets people to capture it, and
then they carry it forward.

00:35:52.400 --> 00:35:54.010
Those are the best brands.

00:35:54.010 --> 00:35:57.672
They're not depending on
you putting that content

00:35:57.672 --> 00:35:58.630
out there all the time.

00:35:58.630 --> 00:36:00.920
People create the
content for themselves.

00:36:00.920 --> 00:36:02.910
They help people
tell their stories.

00:36:02.910 --> 00:36:06.120
And there are people--
everybody has different stories,

00:36:06.120 --> 00:36:07.580
but there are
people that respond,

00:36:07.580 --> 00:36:09.820
there are communities of
people that love and respond

00:36:09.820 --> 00:36:13.680
to stories in different ways.

00:36:13.680 --> 00:36:17.814
Relevance achieves that-- making
people feel better, not worse.

00:36:17.814 --> 00:36:19.230
Having meaning in
this world, even

00:36:19.230 --> 00:36:21.160
if you're talking
about cancer, you

00:36:21.160 --> 00:36:25.100
have to give people something
that touches their compassion,

00:36:25.100 --> 00:36:27.960
their ability to care
for friends and family.

00:36:27.960 --> 00:36:30.930
They don't want to feel
worse then they already do.

00:36:30.930 --> 00:36:33.740
They want to make new
connections, expand.

00:36:33.740 --> 00:36:35.790
There's something
expansive about it.

00:36:35.790 --> 00:36:39.430
It's easy and it's fun to
self-identify with a brand.

00:36:39.430 --> 00:36:41.640
You feel like that brand
is connecting to you.

00:36:41.640 --> 00:36:44.070
I mean, I think Chobani does
a really great job of that.

00:36:44.070 --> 00:36:46.460
For a pretty broad-based
consumer brand,

00:36:46.460 --> 00:36:48.769
Chobani does an awesome
job about speaking

00:36:48.769 --> 00:36:49.810
to people where they are.

00:36:49.810 --> 00:36:52.520
They know who they're trying to
reach, and they do a good job.

00:36:52.520 --> 00:36:54.390
And ultimately,
you're meeting a need

00:36:54.390 --> 00:36:56.200
and you're solving a problem.

00:36:56.200 --> 00:36:59.330
I've told you about the work
that the American Cancer

00:36:59.330 --> 00:37:00.300
Society does.

00:37:00.300 --> 00:37:02.255
That's a great
example of relevance.

00:37:02.255 --> 00:37:03.880
The second one I
would just talk to you

00:37:03.880 --> 00:37:06.420
is a little bit the
Ocean Conservancy.

00:37:06.420 --> 00:37:07.860
Here's an example
of how relevance

00:37:07.860 --> 00:37:09.370
can make a difference.

00:37:09.370 --> 00:37:12.540
They were struggling
with their donations.

00:37:12.540 --> 00:37:16.140
They wanted to get their capital
campaign or their annual gift

00:37:16.140 --> 00:37:19.030
giving campaign-- it wasn't
where they wanted it to be.

00:37:19.030 --> 00:37:22.450
And their messaging was great,
their website was great.

00:37:22.450 --> 00:37:24.880
But it wasn't doing the job.

00:37:24.880 --> 00:37:26.840
What they found
through the research

00:37:26.840 --> 00:37:29.890
was that instead of talking
to people about the ocean's

00:37:29.890 --> 00:37:33.010
health-- like you should
care about the Atlantic Ocean

00:37:33.010 --> 00:37:36.010
because the beaches are cleaner
and it's better fishing,

00:37:36.010 --> 00:37:39.370
and there's no trash,
and marine life survives.

00:37:39.370 --> 00:37:42.300
When people started
connecting the ocean's health

00:37:42.300 --> 00:37:45.700
to their personal health,
that was the a-ha.

00:37:45.700 --> 00:37:50.330
It's like, if that estuary
gets sick, you get sick.

00:37:50.330 --> 00:37:52.470
If the water doesn't
work on our planet,

00:37:52.470 --> 00:37:53.810
that's an enormous problem.

00:37:53.810 --> 00:37:59.030
And if you use the right
combination of messages, A,

00:37:59.030 --> 00:38:01.960
to get people to
care, to inspire them,

00:38:01.960 --> 00:38:04.720
to connect with them, that
makes a huge difference.

00:38:04.720 --> 00:38:07.150
So that turned out
to be the message,

00:38:07.150 --> 00:38:09.800
connecting the ocean's health
with personal health, that

00:38:09.800 --> 00:38:10.780
made the difference.

00:38:10.780 --> 00:38:14.320
And the analytics and the
data behind the campaign

00:38:14.320 --> 00:38:15.510
showed that.

00:38:15.510 --> 00:38:18.220
So that's a fast
